[4] South Africa (Western Cape ex Mpumalanga)
Date: Thu, 27 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Independent Online [edited]
<http://www.int.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=125&art_id=vn20051027121219317C219628>

Cape Town has confirmed its 1st case of typhoid, but provincial health
authorities have moved quickly to urge people not to panic.
The Fish Hoek man has been treated and discharged from False Bay Hospital,
where he was isolated from Wed, 19 Oct 2005, and there are no signs that
the disease has spread.
Typhoid has rocked the Mpumalanga town of Delmas. The affected local man
visited Delmas several weeks ago on church outreach business.
Western Cape Health Department spokesperson Faiza Steyn said yesterday, 26
Oct 2005, that tests on the man had been conducted in Delmas when he first
fell ill. However, these had turned up negative for typhoid. However, the
disease has an incubation period of 10 to 20 days and, when the man
continued feeling ill, he was admitted to False Bay Hospital on 19 Oct 2005.
"His blood was then cultured and reported positive with typhoid fever,"
said Steyn. She added that the patient's isolation and all universal
infection control measures had immediately swung into place at the hospital.
[Byline: Di Caelers]
